{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU_1": {
      "text": "Within this work, subjectivity and consciousness are for the first time established as a primary concern for metaphysics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_2": {
      "text": "Kant likewise concluded that subjectivity, rather than serving as the door into being, instead serves as an impenetrable obstacle to knowledge of things themselves.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_3": {
      "text": "Far from obtaining a more firm foundation, metaphysics was instead deemed impossible.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_4": {
      "text": "What is nonetheless troublesome is the fact that subjectivity is still very much seen as a terrible impasse impeding metaphysical progress.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_5": {
      "text": "Classically construed, metaphysics was understood as the science of being as being.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_6": {
      "text": "Metaphysics both includes subjectivity but was likewise thought to transcend the subject on the basis of the human reflective capacity to 'double back' upon itself in thinking, as it were, to reflect upon the nature of its own encounter.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_7": {
      "text": "Reflection and the desire to know emerge as the foundation of metaphysical inquiry.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_8": {
      "text": "What is in consequence required is a retrieval of the classical Aristotelian conception of metaphysics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_9": {
      "text": "Since Descartes, the history of thinking about being, far from metaphysics, emphasizes instead relational forms of ontology inasmuch as the subject now takes center stage in the account of being.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_10": {
      "text": "For over two centuries metaphysics has suffered serious and in many ways irrecoverable damage on account of confusion and critique.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_11": {
      "text": "Despite this, the science of being remains, awaiting further development, the foundations of which having first been laid down by Aristotle and the scholastics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_12": {
      "text": "Reflection reveals a distinction between being for a subject and being apart from the subject.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_13": {
      "text": "The life of the body is in consequence first on the order of experience.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_14": {
      "text": "From this we might conclude that although the body is first on the order of experience, the ego is first on the order of consciousness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_15": {
      "text": "Recognition of the separate life of the ego implies an act on an entirely different order.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_16": {
      "text": "This conscious act according to which the ego separates itself from the life of the body is here called reflection.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_17": {
      "text": "Through reflection, the embodied relations that hold between being and I rise to the surface and are made known to me.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_18": {
      "text": "Through reflection, the dialectic that emerges involves analysis of identity and difference.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_19": {
      "text": "We in turn discover that metaphysics is possible as a science, nor does subjectivity stand in the way as an obstacle hindering this science.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU_20": {
      "text": "To the contrary, subjectivity coupled with reflection and judgment serve as the door into being and it is through this door, coupled with the desire to know, that further metaphysical inquiry into the nature of being as being finds its point of departure.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
  "relations": [
    {
      "source": "ADU_2",
      "target": "ADU_3",
      "type": "support"
    },
    {
      "source": "ADU_4",
      "target": "ADU_9",
      "type": "support"
    },
    {
